article.headline: Waleskowski's Flyers hand Bearcats first loss
article.linkText: With upset, Dayton snaps 11-game skid vs. Cincy
article.story:
DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- Keith Waleskowski scored 18 points to lead
Dayton to a 75-69 upset of Cincinnati (No. 19 ESPN/USA Today, No. 21 AP) on Saturday night.

	   The 6-foot-9 forward combined strong shooting underneath with a
soft touch from the outside. The victory snapped Cincinnati's
11-game winning streak over the Flyers (3-0).

	   Bearcats coach Bob Huggins, who suffered a massive heart attack
nine weeks ago, kept his cool during the game. However, Huggins
occasionally jawed with the referees or stomped his foot in
frustration at his team's play.

	   The Flyers were able to pound the ball inside and either score
underneath or kick the ball outside for open shots from the
perimeter.

	   Cincinnati (2-1) had trouble getting the ball inside with its
inexperienced front line, forcing the Bearcats to rely heavily on
their outside shooting. Forward Leonard Stokes was often able to
thread his way through the Flyers defense and make high-percentage
shots.

	   Two 3-pointers by Tony Bobbitt enabled the Bearcats to trim
Dayton's lead to 67-64 with 4:37 remaining. But a 3-pointer by
Dayton's Mark Jones followed by a lay-in from Waleskowski put the
game out of reach.

	   In the first half, Dayton built a 12-point lead with 4:34
remaining, but two 3-pointers by Field Williams helped Cincinnati
close within four by halftime.

	   Williams led the Bearcats with 15 points.
